UPDATE public.designers SET biography = $BIO$Thierry Lemaire conceives spaces and furniture of profound sophistication, harmonising the rigour of classical architecture with an organic, almost tactile sensoriality. Working in the great tradition of the French Decorative Arts, he approaches each commission with the panoramic eye of an architecte-ensemblier and the liberated intuition of an artist — pushing his research to the edge of perfection while cultivating the wit that prevents any single style from confining him.

> "When I arrive in Brittany, I taste the ocean."
> — Thierry Lemaire

His signature is unmistakable, yet never static. It is felt in the tension between the raw and the refined, between inventive audacity and discipline; a "French Touch" enriched by local cultural imaginaries that has made him a designer of choice from Paris and Gstaad to Beirut, Marrakech, Geneva and London.

https://res.cloudinary.com/dif1oamtj/image/upload/v1775600674/Screen_Shot_2026-04-08_at_6.23.59_AM_tl1lex.png

**A Breton childhood, an artist-explorer's eye.** Lemaire came of age on the coast of Brittany, where the sea sculpts rock with relentless assault, animates the light of tormented skies and ignites steel with a thousand hues. That foundational dialogue between the elemental and the crafted remains the bedrock of his practice: an instinct for the *genius loci* — the spirit of a place — and for coaxing from each material its most subtle, astonishing effect.

**Architecture, then the Decorative Arts.** During his architectural studies he discovered the spirit of the French Decorative Arts and recognised in them his own deepest inspirations: the nobility of materials, the rigour of line, the elegance of curves; the dialogue between art and industry; the conviction that progress, technique and beauty form a virtuous alliance. From this came his vocation as an *ensemblier* — the desire to orchestrate every element, tangible and intangible, so that structure, volume, furniture, materials, colour, flow and light speak in one voice.

> "Naming a piece *Chevet Voudhir* is a playful wink. *R12* is a tribute to my dog."
> — Thierry Lemaire

**Paris in the 1980s — fertile collisions.** A vibrant coming-of-age in a mythical Paris stimulated his appetite for meaningful encounters, cultural cross-pollination and a cultivated, glamourous hedonism. Deeply influenced by the DJ culture of the era — built on technical mastery, sharing and improvisation — he learned to "mix" disparate universes into unprecedented visual expressions. Years of wandering the aisles of flea markets and antique galleries forged an eclectic, discerning culture of the object that still nourishes his daily practice. Early site experience confirmed a lifelong commitment to hands-on technical mastery: an architect who knows the weight of stone, the grain of timber, the temper of metal.

https://res.cloudinary.com/dif1oamtj/image/upload/v1775599593/Screen_Shot_2026-04-08_at_6.06.08_AM_ocyhty.png

**Projects as sanctuaries.** Lemaire conceives interiors as warm, sensual spaces — simultaneously futuristic and intimate, magnetic and welcoming, energising yet serene. Doors are treated as architectural rituals; surfaces become tactile, sensorial, historical explorations. Every project is a shared human experience, and partners consistently cite the constructive spirit and unwavering efficiency of the studio.

> "One can navigate while maintaining a sense of openness; one can breathe, never feeling confined by walls."
> — A client

**Furniture as totems and XXL jewels.** Alongside his interiors, Lemaire designs furniture and lighting that he describes as an alchemist's endeavour — beginning with the raw potential of matter and arriving at a state of organic sophistication. His pieces are sculptural monuments crafted with the refinement of fine jewellery: singular objects to be experienced from every angle, developed to the exacting standards of collectible design yet always rooted in their function. Bronze, travertine, polished aluminium, noble timbers and stone are his vocabulary; the Orsay coffee table, the Niko sofa collection and the Kedis lamp are among its most celebrated phrases.

> "See the space around it first."
> — Thierry Lemaire

> "The material still lives. It changes the vibration of the piece."
> — A client

**The Gallery, Rue Bonaparte.** From his Saint-Germain-des-Prés gallery at 11 rue Bonaparte, Lemaire stages a scenography in constant metamorphosis — current inspirations, new editions and unique pieces sourced from around the world. His work has been exhibited and represented internationally, including by The Future Perfect (US) and The Rope (Germany), and featured in *AD France*, *Architectural Digest*, *Elle Décoration* and *The World of Interiors*.

**Take away.** Sensual post-modernism. Sophisticated materiality. Controlled dissonance. Luxury craftsmanship.$BIO$
